# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: silent-spring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is one of the oldest and most widely available herbicides and defoliants in the world, having been commercially available since 1945, and is now produced by many chemical companies since the patent on it has long since expired.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It can be found in numerous commercial lawn herbicide mixtures, and is widely used as a weedkiller on cereal crops, pastures, and orchards.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Over 1,500 herbicide products contain 2,4-D as an active ingredient.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D was first reported in 1944 by Franklin D.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The biological activity of 2,4-D as well as the similar hormone herbicides 2,4,5-T, and MCPA were discovered during World War II, a case of multiple discovery by four groups working independently under wartime secrecy in the United Kingdom and the United States: William G.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Templeman and associates at Imperial Chemical Industries (ICI) in the UK; Philip S.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Nutman and associates at Rothamsted Research in the UK; Franklin D.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Jones and associates at the American Chemical Paint Company; and Ezra Kraus, John W.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Mitchell, and associates at the University of Chicago and the United States Department of Agriculture.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] All four groups were subject to wartime secrecy laws and did not follow the usual procedures of publication and patent disclosure.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In December 1942, following a meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture the Rothamsted and ICI workers pooled resources and Nutman moved to Jealott's Hill to join the ICI effort.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The first scientific publication describing the 2,4-D structure and plant growth regulating activity was by Percy Zimmerman and Albert Hitchcock at the Boyce Thompson Institute, who were not the original inventors.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The precise sequence of early 2,4-D discovery events and publications has been discussed.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] William Templeman found that when indole-3-acetic acid (IAA), a naturally occurring auxin, was used at high concentrations, it could stop plant growth.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In 1940, he published his finding that IAA killed broadleaf plants within a cereal field.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] MCPA was discovered at about that time by his ICI group.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In the United States, a similar search for an acid with a longer half life, i.e., a metabolically and environmentally more stable compound, led to 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4-D) and 2,4,5-trichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4,5-T), both phenoxy herbicides and analogs of IAA.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Robert Pokorny, an industrial chemist for the C.B.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Dolge Company in Westport, Connecticut, published their synthesis in 1941.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D was not used as a chemical warfare agent during the war.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The Allies of World War II were looking for a chemical to starve Nazi Germany and Japan into submission by killing their potato and rice crops, but 2,4-D was found to be ineffective for that purpose, because both crops tolerate it.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Within a year after the war ended, 2,4-D was commercially released as an herbicide to control broadleaf weeds in grain crops such as rice and wheat, and in the 1950s it was registered in the United States to control size and enhance skin color in potatoes without affecting yields.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The first publication of 2,4-D's use as a selective herbicide came in 1944.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The ability of 2,4-D to control broadleaf weeds in turf was documented soon thereafter, in 1944.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Starting in 1945, the American Chemical Paint Company brought 2,4-D to market as an herbicide called "Weedone".
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It revolutionized weed control, as it was the first compound that, at low doses, could selectively control dicotyledons (broadleaf plants), but not most monocotyledons — narrowleaf crops, such as wheat, maize (corn), rice, and similar cereal grass crops.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] At a time when labor was scarce and the need for increased food production was large, it literally "replaced the hoe".
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Its effectiveness, together with its non-corrosive, non-explosive and seemingly non-irritating or poisonous qualities, led to it being considered the best all-around herbicide by 1946.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is one of the ingredients in Agent Orange, an herbicide that was widely used during the Malayan Emergency and the Vietnam War.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] However, 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzodioxin (TCDD), a contaminant in the production of another ingredient in Agent Orange, 2,4,5-T, was the cause of the adverse health effects associated with Agent Orange.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In the 2000s, Dow AgroSciences developed a new choline salt version of 2,4-D (2,4-D choline) that Dow included in its "Enlist Duo" herbicide along with glyphosate and an agent that reduces drift; the choline salt form of 2,4-D is less volatile than 2,4-D.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is a member of the phenoxy family of herbicides.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It is manufactured from chloroacetic acid and 2,4-dichlorophenol, which is itself produced by chlorination of phenol.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Alternatively, it is produced by the chlorination of phenoxyacetic acid.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The production processes may create several contaminants including di-, tri-, and tetrachlorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin isomers and *N*-nitrosamines, as well as monochlorophenol.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is a synthetic auxin that induces uncontrolled growth and eventually death in susceptible plants.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It is absorbed through the leaves and is translocated to the meristems of the plant.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Uncontrolled, unsustainable growth ensues, causing stem curl-over, leaf withering, and eventual plant death.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is typically applied as an amine salt, but more potent ester versions exist, as well.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is primarily used as a selective herbicide that kills many terrestrial and aquatic broadleaf weeds, but not grasses.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D can be found in commercial lawn herbicide mixtures, which often contain other active ingredients including mecoprop and dicamba.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] A variety of sectors use products containing 2,4-D to kill weeds and unwanted vegetation.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In agriculture, it was the first herbicide for selective killing of weeds but not crops.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It has been used since 1945 to control broad-leafed weeds in pastures, orchards, and cereal crops such as corn, oats, rice, and wheat.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Cereals, in particular, have excellent tolerance to 2,4-D when it is applied before planting.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is the cheapest way for farmers to control winter annual weeds by spraying in the fall, often at the lowest recommended rate.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] This is particularly effective before planting beans, peas, lentils, and chickpeas.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The estimated use of 2,4-D in US agriculture is mapped by the US Geological Survey.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In 2019, the latest date for which figures are available, this reached 45,000,000 pounds (20,000,000 kg) annually.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In domestic lawn and garden maintenance, 2,4-D is commonly used.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In forestry, it is used for stump treatment, trunk injection, and selective control of brush in conifer forests.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Along roadways, railways, and power lines, it is used to control weeds and brush which might interfere with safe operation and damage equipment.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Along waterways, it is used to control aquatic weeds that might interfere with boating, fishing, and swimming or clog irrigation and hydroelectric equipment.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It is often used by government agencies to control the spread of invasive, noxious, and non-native weed species and prevent them from crowding out native species, and also to control many poisonous weeds such as poison ivy and poison oak.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D has been used in laboratories for plant research as a supplement in plant cell culture media such as MS medium since at least 1962.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is used in plant cell cultures as a dedifferentiation (callus induction) hormone.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] It is classified as an auxin plant hormone derivative.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Men who work with 2,4-D are at risk for abnormally shaped sperm and thus fertility problems; the risk depends on the amount and duration of exposure and other personal factors.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Environmental Protection Agency, "The toxicity of 2,4-D depends on its chemical forms, including salts, esters, and an acid form.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D generally has low toxicity for humans, except certain acid and salt forms can cause eye irritation.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Swimming is restricted for 24 hours after application of certain 2,4-D products applied to control aquatic weeds to avoid eye irritation." As of 2005 the median lethal dose or LD50 determined in acute toxicity rat studies was 639 mg/kg.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Urinary alkalinisation has been used in acute poisoning, but evidence to support its use is poor.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The International Agency for Research on Cancer classifies 2,4-D as a possible carcinogen to humans while the United States Environmental Protection Agency does not.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), said 2,4-D was classified as "possibly carcinogenic to humans (Group 2B), based on inadequate evidence in humans and limited evidence in experimental animals".
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In June 2015 the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer confirmed its 1987 classification of 2,4-D as a possible carcinogen.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] On August 8, 2007, the EPA issued a ruling that existing data do not support a link between human cancer and 2,4-D exposure.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] A 1995 panel of 13 scientists reviewing studies on the carcinogenicity of 2,4-D had divided opinions.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] None of the scientists thought the weight of the evidence indicated that 2,4-D was a "known" or "probable" cause of human cancer.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Two panelists believed it unlikely that 2,4-D can cause cancer in humans.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In a prior 1987 report the IARC classified some chlorphenoxy herbicides including 2,4-D, MCPA and 2,4,5-T as a group as class 2B carcinogens - "possibly carcinogenic to humans".
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D has been linked to lymphoma and bladder cancer in dogs.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] A July 2013 *Four Corners* investigation found elevated levels of dioxins in a generic version of 2,4-D, one of Australia's most widely used herbicides.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] When radioactively labeled 2,4-D was fed to livestock, 90% or more of the total radioactive residue (TRR) was shed in urine unchanged or as conjugated forms of 2,4-D.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] A relatively small portion of 2,4-D was metabolized into dichlorophenol, dichloroanisole, 4-chlorophenoxyacetic acid (6.9% of the TRR in milk), and 2,4-dichlorophenol (5% of the TRR in milk; 7.3% of the TRR in eggs and 4% of the TRR in chicken liver).
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Residue levels in kidney were the highest.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Owing to the longevity and extent of use, 2,4-D has been evaluated several times by regulators and review committees.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D amine salts and esters are not persistent under most environmental conditions.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The degradation of 2,4-D is rapid (half life of 6.2 days) in aerobic mineral soils.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is broken down by microbes in soil, in processes that involve hydroxylation, cleavage of the acid side-chain, decarboxylation, and ring opening.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The ethyl hexyl form of the compound is rapidly hydrolyzed in soil and water to form the 2,4-D acid.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D has a low binding affinity in mineral soils and sediment, and in those conditions is considered intermediately to highly mobile, and therefore likely to leach if not degraded.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In aerobic aquatic environments, the half life is 15 days.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In anaerobic aquatic environments 2,4-D is more persistent, with a half life of 41 to 333 days.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D has been detected in streams and shallow groundwater at low concentrations, in both rural and urban areas.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Some ester forms are highly toxic to fish and other aquatic life.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] "The ester forms of 2,4-D can be highly toxic to fish and other aquatic life.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D generally has moderate toxicity to birds and mammals, is slightly toxic to fish and aquatic invertebrates, and is practically nontoxic to honeybees" per EPA.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] A number of 2,4-D-degrading bacteria have been isolated and characterized from a variety of environmental habitats.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Metabolic pathways for the compound's degradation have been available for many years, and genes encoding 2,4-D catabolism have been identified for several organisms.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] As a result of the extensive metadata on environmental behavior, physiology, and genetics, 2,4-D was the first herbicide for which the bacteria actively responsible for *in situ*degradation were demonstrated.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] This was accomplished using the technique of DNA-based stable isotope probing, which enables a microbial function (activity), such as degrading a chemical, to be linked with the organism's identity without the need to culture the organism involved.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Maximum residue limits were first set in the EU in 2002 and re-evaluated in 2011 by the European Food Safety Authority, which concluded that the codex maximum residue limits were "not expected to be of concern for European consumers".
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The total chronic exposure represented less than 10% of the acceptable daily intake (ADI).
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D is currently not approved for use on lawns and gardens in Denmark, Norway, Kuwait, and the Canadian provinces of Québec and Ontario.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] 2,4-D use is severely restricted in the country of Belize.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In 2008, Dow AgroScience, LLC, sued the Canadian government for allowing Quebec to ban 2,4-D, but settled in 2011.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In 2012, EPA denied the petition filed November 6, 2008, by the Natural Resources Defense Council to revoke all tolerances and to cancel all registrations of 2,4-D.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] EPA stated that new study and EPA's comprehensive review confirmed EPA's previous finding that the 2,4-D tolerances are safe at anticipated exposure.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] The estimated annual use of 2,4-D in US agriculture is mapped by the US Geological Service.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In October 2014, the US EPA registered Enlist Duo, an herbicide containing the less volatile 2,4-D choline salt, glyphosate, and an antidrift agent, for use in six states: Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Ohio, South Dakota, and Wisconsin.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In November 2015, the EPA attempted to withdraw its own approval of Enlist Duo, as a result of legal actions against both the agency and Dow by two U.S. groups.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] However, while it was implied that the approval was "gone" because of the action, in fact, Enlist Duo was still approved pending a decision by the courts.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] On January 25, 2016, the US Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals denied EPA's motion to vacate its Enlist Duo registration.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Dow stated the product would be available in 15 US states and Canada for the 2016 crop season.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] On August 21, 2013, the Australian Pesticides and Veterinary Medicines Authority (APVMA) banned selected 2,4-D high volatile ester (HVE) products due to their environmental hazards.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] HVE 2,4-D products had already been banned in Europe and North America for 20 years; low volatile ester products continue to be available in Australia and worldwide.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In July 2013 APVMA published their report findings.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In 2010, Dow published that it had created genetically modified soybeans made resistant to 2,4-D by insertion of a bacterial aryloxyalkanoate dioxygenase gene, *aad1*.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] Dow intended it to be used as an alternative or complement to Roundup Ready crops due to the increasing prevalence of glyphosate-resistant weeds.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] As of April 2014, genetically modified maize and soybeans resistant to 2,4-D and glyphosate have been approved in Canada.
[src:silent-spring/2-4-d] In September 2014, the USDA also approved Dow's maize and soybeans, and in October, the EPA registered the "Enlist Duo" herbicide containing 2,4-D and glyphosate.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The series centers on a diverse group of characters, mainly scientists, who encounter an extraterrestrial civilization, triggering numerous threats and profound changes for humanity.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] While the two earlier adaptations, the animated *The Three-Body Problem in Minecraft* (2014–2020) and the live-action *Three-Body* (2023), were entirely in the novels' original Mandarin, *3 Body Problem* is primarily in English with some Mandarin.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] It also alters parts of the original setting in China to include foreign characters and locations, particularly in the United Kingdom.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] This was Benioff and Weiss' first television project since the conclusion of their series *Game of Thrones* (2011–2019).
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] It received positive reviews, with praise towards its cast, ambition, and production values.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The series received six Primetime Emmy Award nominations, including Outstanding Drama Series.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In May 2024, the series was renewed for a second and third season.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The second season is set to premiere in 2026.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Chinese astrophysicist Ye Wenjie runs into trouble with the authorities after witnessing her father's death during a struggle session in the Cultural Revolution.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] She is sent to a secret military base because of her scientific background, where she is racing against other countries to make first contact with aliens during the Cold War.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] While there, she makes a choice that affects humanity's future.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In present-day London, a series of mysterious suicides and phenomena lead a government investigator and a group of friends called the "Oxford Five" into a mystery of extraterrestrial origin.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] It was announced in September 2020 that David Benioff and D.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Weiss were developing a television adaptation of the novel at Netflix, with Alexander Woo co-writing alongside them.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Benioff and Weiss have said they are prepared to adapt the whole trilogy, which they expect to require three or four seasons.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] On December 25, 2020, Lin Qi, founder of Yoozoo Games and an executive producer on *3 Body Problem*, died after ingesting a poisoned beverage, with four others becoming ill.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] An executive at Yoozoo Games, Xu Yao, was sentenced to death for murder in March 2024, the day after the series premiered on Netflix.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Lin had purchased the rights to the book franchise and hired Xu Yao, a lawyer, in 2017, to manage the rights to Liu's novels; the poisonings were an attempt by Xu to take control of the subsidiary company that owned the rights to the series.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] On May 15, 2024, Netflix renewed the series for a second season.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] On May 31, 2024, Benioff, Weiss and Woo confirmed that the series was renewed for seasons 2–3 during the official Television Academy *3 Body Problem* panel at the Netflix FYSEE space at Sunset Las Palmas in Los Angeles.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] According to Benioff, he had already worked with UK-based staff for *Game of Thrones* and wanted to use them in this production, and Benioff stated that the need to coordinate among those staff influenced the choice of the UK as a setting in *3 Body Problem*.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In August 2021, Eiza González entered negotiations to join the cast.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The same month, Derek Tsang was hired to direct the pilot episode.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] González would be confirmed as joining the cast by that October, with additional castings including Benedict Wong, Tsai Chin, John Bradley, Liam Cunningham and Jovan Adepo.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In June 2022, Jonathan Pryce, Rosalind Chao, Ben Schnetzer and Eve Ridley were added to cast.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In November 2025, Claudia Doumit, Ellie de Lange, Alfie Allen, David Yip, and Jordan Sunshine joined to the cast for the second season.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Production on the series began on November 8, 2021, with principal photography taking place in the United Kingdom.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Filming took place in London over a nine-month shoot between October 2021 and mid 2022.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] At Netflix's Tudum 2022 event, Alexander Woo, David Benioff, and D.B.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Weiss announced that the production of the first season was completed.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Netflix reportedly spent $20 million per episode, for a total budget of $160 million for the first season.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Filming of season two started November 26, 2025 in Budapest, Hungary, with season three reportedly planned to be filmed back-to-back.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The review aggregator Rotten Tomatoes reported a 78% approval rating with an average rating of 6.9/10, based on 115 critic reviews.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Ben Travers of *IndieWire* gave a critical review, writing that "*3 Body Problem* is a sprawling drag, at turns disorienting in its use of inconsistent CGI to convey the story's momentousness and aggravating in its approach to character development and existential quandaries.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The plot is easy enough to track, but the relief of realizing you can keep up with this motley crew of scientist pals—as they try to figure out why so many of their peers are dying off—is short-lived." Charles Pulliam-Moore of *The Verge* gave a mixed review, writing that "though David Benioff, D.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Weiss, and Alexander Woo's *3 Body Problem* is impressive, it really feels like just an introduction to Cixin Liu's deeper ideas." He opined that future seasons could explore the world of Liu's later novels.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] In response to social media criticism about racebending, cast member Benedict Wong said that Liu had given the showrunners his blessing to move the story towards a global one.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Wong also cited the presence of several Asian cast members including himself, Jess Hong, Rosalind Chao and Zine Tseng.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Hong and Chao also said that the Netflix adaptation preserved the novel's depiction of the Cultural Revolution and its legacy.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Hong said that the adaptation sought to "globalize a story that was very heavily Eastern-focused into a Western perspective, a global perspective.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] Aja Romano of *Vox* suggested that the media exaggerated Chinese social media nationalistic outrage against the Netflix show.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] They found that the Chinese audience "praising the show and criticizing it in equal parts", and shared similar critical commentary to the ones from the Western audience, underscoring that criticism of the show is universal.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] The original author, Liu Cixin, commented on the series, saying, "I enjoyed the part of the series where many characters were added, and their relationships were explored.
[src:silent-spring/3-body-problem-tv-series] However, it was strange how all these characters seemed to know each other already.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] As a practical matter, mites are a paraphyletic grouping, and mites and ticks are usually treated as a single group.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] Acaricides are also being used in attempts to stop rhinoceros poaching.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] Holes are drilled into the horn of a sedated rhino and acaricide is pumped in and pressurized.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] Should the horn be consumed by humans as in traditional Chinese medicine, it is expected to cause nausea, stomachache, and diarrhea, or convulsions, depending on the quantity, but not fatalities.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] Signs posted at wildlife refuges that the rhinos therein have been treated are thus expected to deter poaching.
[src:silent-spring/acaricide] The original idea grew out of research into using the horn as a reservoir for one-time tick treatments; the acaricide is selected to be safe for the rhino, oxpeckers, vultures, and other animals in the preserve's ecosystem.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] His style has been described as involving, "whiplash digressions, menacing atmospherics and arpeggiated scores, and the near-psychedelic compilation of archival footage", narrated by Curtis himself with "patrician economy and assertion".
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Adam Curtis was born in Dartford in Kent, and raised in nearby Platt.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] His father was Martin Curtis (1917–2002), a cinematographer with a socialist background.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis won a county scholarship and attended the Sevenoaks School.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] It was there that an influential art teacher introduced him to the work of Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis completed a Bachelor of Arts degree in human sciences at Mansfield College, Oxford.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] He began a PhD and taught in politics, but ultimately became disillusioned with academia and decided to leave.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis applied to the BBC and was hired to make a film for one of its training courses, comparing designer clothes in music videos to the design of weapons.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] He was subsequently given a post on *That's Life!*, a magazine series that juxtaposed hard-hitting investigations and light-hearted content.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] He was a film director on *Out of Court*, a BBC Two legal series, from 1980 until 1982.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis is inspired by the sociologist Max Weber, who, he argues, challenged the "crude, left-wing, vulgar Marxism that says that everything happens because of economic forces within society".
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis has answered questions on his politics in interviews over his career but has answered inconsistently, making it hard to label his politics.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In a 2012 interview, Curtis remarked on his political outlook stating fondness for libertarian ideas but states his politics are unique and differ depending on the issue.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In a 2021 interview, Curtis stated having sympathies to radicalism and that progressivism is his politics.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In a 2022 interview, Curtis reiterated the neoconservative interpretation of "The Century of the Self" but added it is not what he himself believes.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] He has also cited Robert Rauschenberg and Émile Zola as creative influences.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis makes extensive use of archive footage in his documentaries.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] He has acknowledged the influence of recordings made by Erik Durschmied and is "constantly using his stuff in my films".
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Discussing his process in an interview with fellow documentary-maker Jon Ronson for *Vice*, Curtis said his extensive work with footage acquired from the BBC Archives is often led by "instinct and imagination", with the aim of creating "a mood that gives power and force to the story I'm telling".
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Instead of specially composed music, which Curtis has said "creates a sort of monoculture", he uses tracks from a variety of genres, decades, and countries, as well as sound effects that he discovers on old tapes.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] According to a profile of Curtis by Tim Adams, published in *The Observer*: "If there has been a theme in Curtis's work ... it has been to look at how different elites have tried to impose an ideology on their times, and the tragicomic consequences of those attempts".
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In 2005, Curtis received the Golden Gate Persistence of Vision Award at the San Francisco International Film Festival.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In 2006, he was given the Alan Clarke Award for Outstanding Creative Contribution to Television at the British Academy Television Awards.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In 2009, the Sheffield International Documentary Festival gave Curtis the Inspiration Award for inspiring viewers and other documentary filmmakers.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] In 2015, he was awarded the True Vision Award by the True/False Film Fest.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis's critics have accused him of exaggeration and distortion, even wilful misrepresentation.
[src:silent-spring/adam-curtis] Curtis administered a blog subtitled 'The Medium and the Message' hosted by the BBC and updated between 2009 and 2016.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] According to IRS filings, the organization spent money entirely on executive compensation, with no program expenses of any kind.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] It has been described as a front group established to discredit environmentalists.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] In documents obtained during state litigation against tobacco companies, founder Roger Bate described the organization's purpose as part of a larger strategy to portray first-world environmentalists as unconcerned with Black Africans.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] James Lawrence Powell lists Africa Fighting Malaria as a greenscamming organization that is engaged in climate change denial, a statement that is shared by Haydn Washington and John Cook, who also note that it has been funded by ExxonMobil.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] According to Powell, the website of Africa Fighting Malaria features articles and commentaries opposing ambitious climate mitigation concepts, even though the dangers of malaria could be exacerbated by global warming.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] Formed in 2000, AFM's staff members had links with a range of right-wing and free market think tanks including the Competitive Enterprise Institute, Institute of Economic Affairs and Tech Central Station.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] AFM promoted the pesticide DDT as a means of fighting malaria.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] It asserted that global health organizations must be free to employ all available tools to fight malaria and that the limited use of DDT for spraying homes and hospitals is a powerful and necessary tool in this fight.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] AFM ran a "Save Children From Malaria" campaign designed to prevent the Stockholm Convention from banning the use of DDT.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] AFM has not published an Annual Report, or any research, since 2011.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] The AFM website republishes articles by AFM on a variety of topics, as well as articles on malaria from other sources.
[src:silent-spring/africa-fighting-malaria] On its website AFM stated that it "receives its funding from a number of different sources, however because of the nature of our work we have a policy of not accepting funds from any government, the insectcides industry or the pharmaceutical industry".
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The **Agricultural Research Service** (**ARS**) is the principal in-house research agency of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS is one of four agencies in USDA's Research, Education and Economics mission area.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS is charged with extending the nation's scientific knowledge and solving agricultural problems through its four national program areas: nutrition, food safety and quality; animal production and protection; natural resources and sustainable agricultural systems; and crop production and protection.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS research focuses on solving problems affecting Americans every day.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Headquarters is located in the Jamie L.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Whitten Building on Independence Avenue in Washington, D.C., and the headquarters staff is located at the George Washington Carver Center (GWCC) in Beltsville, Maryland.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] For 2023, the budget grew to $1.9 billion.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS conducts scientific research for the American public.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS research complements the work of state colleges and universities, agricultural experiment stations, other federal and state agencies, and the private sector.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS research may often focus on regional issues that have national implications, and where there is a clear federal role.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS also provides information on its research results to USDA action and regulatory agencies and to several other federal regulatory agencies, including the Food and Drug Administration and the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS disseminates much of its research results through scientific journals, technical publications, *Agricultural Research* magazine, and other forums.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Information is also distributed through ARS's National Agricultural Library (NAL).
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS has more than 150 librarians and other information specialists who work at two NAL locations—the Abraham Lincoln Building in Beltsville, Maryland; and the DC Reference Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] NAL provides reference and information services, document delivery, interlibrary loan and interlibrary borrowing services to a variety of audiences.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Prior to the inception of ARS, agricultural research was first conducted under the umbrella of the Agricultural Department in the U.S.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] It was created to collect statistics, distribute seeds and compile and distribute pertinent information.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] In 1862 the USDA was created and agricultural research was moved to its department.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] That same year, the department issued its first research bulletin on the sugar content of grape varietals and their suitability for wine.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Six years later the USDA would begin its first research on animal diseases, specifically hog cholera, which was causing devastating losses at the time.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] In the early 1900s the USDA began analyzing food composition and the first studies of nutrition and the effects of cooking and processing foods were conducted.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Finally, in 1953 the Agricultural Research Service was created to be the USDA's primary scientific research agency.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS supports more than 2,000 scientists and post docs working on approximately 690 research projects within 15 National Programs at more than 90 research locations.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The ARS is divided into 5 geographic areas: Midwest Area, Northeast Area, Pacific West Area, Plains Area, and Southeast Area.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The research centers focus on innovation in agricultural practices, pest control, health, and nutrition among other things.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Work at these facilities has given life to numerous products, processes, and technologies.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC) in Beltsville, Maryland, is the world's largest agricultural research complex.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Other D.C. area locations include the United States National Agricultural Library and the United States National Arboretum.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS also has six major human nutrition research centers that focus on solving a wide spectrum of human nutrition questions by providing authoritative, peer-reviewed, science-based evidence.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The centers are located in Arkansas, Maryland, Texas, North Dakota, Massachusetts (the Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging), and California.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] ARS scientists at these centers study the role of food and dietary components in human health from conception to advanced age.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The ARS also offers the Culture Collection, which is the largest public collection of microorganisms in the world, containing approximately 93,000 strains of bacteria and fungi.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Culture Collection is housed at the National Center for Agricultural Utilization Research (NCAUR).
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] There is also a collection of entomopathogenic fungi, called ARSEF, at the Robert W.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Holley Center for Agriculture and Health in Ithaca, New York.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Horticultural Research Laboratory in Fort Pierce, Florida, and the U.S.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] National Poultry Research Center in Athens, Georgia.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Other notable ARS facilities include Northern Great Basin Experimental Range in Oregon, and formerly the Plum Island Animal Disease Center off Long Island.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Several ARS research units focus on pests, diseases, and management practices of horticultural crops.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The Cereal Disease Laboratory is located on the campus of the University of Minnesota in Saint Paul.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] It primarily hosts research into rusts and *Fusaria* of cereals.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The San Joaquin Valley Agricultural Sciences Center in Parlier, California conducts research on specialty crops including grapes, citrus, almonds, alfalfa, peaches, pomegranates, and many others.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Several research locations throughout the US also house germplasm collections of plant species important for agricultural and industrial uses as part of the **National Genetic Resources Program**.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] From the very beginning the Department of Agriculture and in turn the Agricultural Research Service has been focused on improving not only the farming industry but also the quality of food and the health of Americans.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] In 1985, technology to produce lactose-free milk, yogurt, and ice cream was developed through the Agricultural Research Service.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The grape breeding program, currently located in Parlier, CA which began in 1923, developed seedless grapes and continues to release new grapevine varieties with improved traits.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Citrus and Subtropical Products Laboratory in Winter Haven, Florida, actively works to improve the taste of orange juice concentrate.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The Agricultural Research Service had a *Toxoplasma gondii* (*T. gondii*) research program, which experimented on cats infected with the parasite, from 1982 until 2018.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The prevalence of *T. gondii* parasite has been reduced by 50% in the U.S.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] As of September 2018, which the ARS claims is a result of their research.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] The USDA has since discontinued the use of cats in their research amid acute accusations of animal abuse, and a lack of meaningful contribution to the field in recent years (only three of thirteen papers published about *T. gondii* by the ARS were published after the year 2000).
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] More recently, the ARS has focused research on genetics and plant and animal DNA.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Their research has developed pest-resistant corn, faster growing plants and fish, and a focus on plant and animal genome research and mapping.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-research-service] Outside of scientific research, the ARS has worked to release databases on food components in order to assist consumers with making informed decisions about food choices.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Adjuvants may be part of an already formulated pesticide as purchased (*in-can* adjuvants), or may be added separately when the spray solution is being prepared (*tank mix* adjuvant).
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Nearly all pesticides are sold by the manufacturers already formulated, and this formulation is effective, but not for all applications.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Those applications may then profit from an in-tank adjuvant.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Annual worldwide adjuvant sales are estimated to be worth more than $1.5 billion, most of which is used by manufacturers in-can.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] The use-rate on the pesticide label is mandatory by law.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] If an adjuvant improves the effectiveness of a pesticide, so that the farmer feels confident in spraying a lower amount, this is only legally allowed if the information on the pesticide label allows it.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] In the United States, adjuvants are essentially unregulated except in a few isolated cases.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] The states of Washington and California require that adjuvants be registered before they can be sold.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Other states may or may not regulate adjuvants at some level.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] There is no federal regulation of tank mix adjuvants.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] However, the industry itself has several efforts underway in order to self regulate the products.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] The ASTM International (ASTM) E35.22 committee is the committee that defines agricultural tank mix claims for the industry.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] The standard E1519 defines the various claims that an adjuvant may make and reference the methods by which the claim may be proven.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] The methods are tests, which when applied to a given sample, prove that the material meets the claimed standard.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Supporting the activities of ASTM is the Council of Producers & Distributors of Agrotechnology (CPDA), an organization of inert (or other) ingredient and adjuvant manufacturers.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] CPDA offers participating companies the ability to self-certify their spray adjuvant products in the US by creating certain minimum standards that must be met in order to receive the CPDA stamp of certification.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] In Canada, adjuvants are regulated by the Pest Management Regulatory Agency (PMRA) section of Health Canada.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Each adjuvant must be tested and be proven to be safe and effective with every active ingredient with which it will be used.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] This much more stringent requirement prevents both the widespread use and questionable content present in the United States.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] In the UK, the Chemical Regulations Directorate (CRD), part of the Health and Safety Executive, oversees the use of adjuvants.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] CRD defines an adjuvant as a substance other than water which is not in itself a pesticide but which enhances or is intended to enhance the effectiveness of the pesticide with which it is used.
[src:silent-spring/agricultural-spray-adjuvant] Adjuvants for use with agricultural pesticides have been categorised as extenders, wetting agents, sticking agents and fogging agents.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In the late 1950s, Carson began to work on environmental conservation, especially environmental problems that she believed (and would later learn) were caused by synthetic pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The result of her research was *Silent Spring*, which brought environmental concerns to the American public.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The book was met with fierce opposition by chemical companies, but it swayed public opinion and led to a reversal in US pesticide policy, a nationwide ban on DDT for agricultural uses, and an environmental movement that led to the creation of the US Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In 2006, *Silent Spring* was named one of the 25 greatest science books of all time by the editors of *Discover* magazine.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In the mid-1940s, Carson became concerned about the use of synthetic pesticides, many of which had been developed through the military funding of science after World War II.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Landowners in Long Island filed a suit to have the spraying stopped, and many in affected regions followed the case closely.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Though the suit was lost, the Supreme Court granted petitioners the right to gain injunctions against potential environmental damage in the future, laying the basis for later environmental actions.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson later wrote that this letter prompted her to study the environmental problems caused by the overuse of chemical pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The Audubon Naturalist Society actively opposed chemical spraying programs and recruited Carson to help publicize the US government's spraying practices and related research.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson began the four-year project of *Silent Spring* by gathering examples of environmental damage attributed to DDT.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] White and a number of journalists and scientists to her cause.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By 1958, Carson had arranged a book deal, with plans to co-write with *Newsweek* science journalist Edwin Diamond.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] However, when *The New Yorker* commissioned a long and well-paid article on the topic from Carson, she began considering writing more than the introduction and conclusion as planned; soon it became a solo project.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Diamond would later write one of the harshest critiques of *Silent Spring*.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] As her research progressed, Carson found a sizable community of scientists who were documenting the physiological and environmental effects of pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] She took advantage of her personal connections with many government scientists, who supplied her with confidential information on the subject.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By 1959, the USDA's Agricultural Research Service responded to the criticism by Carson and others with a public service film, *Fire Ants on Trial*; Carson called it "flagrant propaganda" that ignored the dangers that spraying pesticides posed to humans and wildlife.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] That spring, Carson wrote a letter, published in *The Washington Post*, that attributed the recent decline in bird populations—in her words, the "silencing of birds"—to pesticide overuse.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The same year, the 1957, 1958, and 1959 crops of US cranberries were found to contain high levels of the herbicide aminotriazole and the sale of all cranberry products was halted.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson attended the ensuing FDA hearings on revising pesticide regulations; she was discouraged by the aggressive tactics of the chemical industry representatives, which included expert testimony that was firmly contradicted by the bulk of the scientific literature she had been studying.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] She also wondered about the possible "financial inducements behind certain pesticide programs".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Research at the National Library of Medicine of the National Institutes of Health brought Carson into contact with medical researchers investigating the gamut of cancer-causing chemicals.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Of particular significance was the work of National Cancer Institute researcher and founding director of the environmental cancer section Wilhelm Hueper, who classified many pesticides as carcinogens.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By 1960, Carson had sufficient research material and the writing was progressing rapidly.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] She had investigated hundreds of individual incidents of pesticide exposure and the resulting human sickness and ecological damage.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In January 1960, she suffered an illness which kept her bedridden for weeks, delaying the book.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] As she was nearing full recovery in March, she discovered cysts in her left breast, requiring a mastectomy.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By December that year, Carson discovered that she had breast cancer, which had metastasized.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Her research was also delayed by revision work for a new edition of *The Sea Around Us*, and by a collaborative photo essay with Erich Hartmann.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Most of the research and writing was done by the fall of 1960, except for a discussion of recent research on biological controls and investigations of some new pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] However, further health troubles delayed the final revisions in 1961 and early 1962.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The work's title was inspired by a poem by John Keats, "La Belle Dame sans Merci", which contained the lines "The sedge is wither'd from the lake, And no birds sing." "Silent Spring" was initially suggested as a title for the chapter on birds.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By August 1961, Carson agreed to the suggestion of her literary agent Marie Rodell: *Silent Spring* would be a metaphorical title for the entire book—suggesting a bleak future for the whole natural world—rather than a literal chapter title about the absence of birdsong.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] With Carson's approval, editor Paul Brooks at Houghton Mifflin arranged for illustrations by Louis and Lois Darling, who also designed the cover.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The final writing was the first chapter, "A Fable for Tomorrow", which was intended to provide the fact that something like the story in the book could happen any time in the near future.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By mid-1962, Brooks and Carson had largely finished the editing and were planning to promote the book by sending the manuscript to select individuals for final suggestions.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In *Silent Spring*, Carson relied on evidence from two New York state organic farmers, Marjorie Spock and Mary Richards, and that of biodynamic farming advocate Ehrenfried Pfeiffer in developing her case against DDT.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The overarching theme of *Silent Spring* is the powerful—and often negative—effect humans have on the natural world.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson's main argument is that pesticides have detrimental effects on the environment; she says these are more properly termed "biocides" because their effects are rarely limited to solely targeting pests.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] DDT is a prime example, but other synthetic pesticides—many of which are subject to bioaccumulation—are scrutinized.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson accuses the chemical industry of intentionally spreading disinformation and public officials of accepting industry claims uncritically.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Most of the book is devoted to pesticides' effects on natural ecosystems, but four chapters detail cases of human pesticide poisoning, cancer, and other illnesses attributed to pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson predicts increased consequences in the future, especially since targeted pests may develop resistance to pesticides and weakened ecosystems fall prey to unanticipated invasive species.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The book closes with a call for a biotic approach to pest control as an alternative to chemical pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson never called for an outright ban on DDT.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson also said that "Malaria programmes are threatened by resistance among mosquitoes", and quoted the advice given by the director of Holland's Plant Protection Service: "Practical advice should be 'Spray as little as you possibly can' rather than 'Spray to the limit of your capacity'.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] At the time the book was written, environmental issues were excluded from mainstream political conversation in America.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] After the program, an increased number of birds, cattle, horses and other wildlife were found dead in the areas where the pesticides had been sprayed.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] To make matters worse, the heptachlor and dieldrin sprayed accomplished nothing, instead creating more infested areas.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Had the government researched the impact the chemicals could have on wildlife they could have prevented the deaths and environmental damage and saved the taxpayer's money.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Overall, *Silent Spring* not only uncovered the many negative effects pesticides have on the environment but also asked for environmental issues to be discussed and treated seriously within the political sphere.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson and the others involved with publication of *Silent Spring* expected fierce criticism and were concerned about the possibility of being sued for libel.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson was undergoing radiation therapy for her cancer and expected to have little energy to defend her work and respond to critics.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In preparation for the anticipated attacks, Carson and her agent attempted to amass prominent supporters before the book's release.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Most of the book's scientific chapters were reviewed by scientists with relevant expertise, among whom Carson found strong support.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson attended the White House Conference on Conservation in May 1962; Houghton Mifflin distributed proof copies of *Silent Spring* to many of the delegates and promoted the upcoming serialization in *The New Yorker*.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson also sent a proof copy to Supreme Court Associate Justice William O.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Douglas, a long-time environmental advocate who had argued against the court's rejection of the Long Island pesticide spraying case and had provided Carson with some of the material included in her chapter on herbicides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Though *Silent Spring* had generated a fairly high level of interest based on pre-publication promotion, this became more intense with its serialization, which began in the June 16, 1962, issue.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] This brought the book to the attention of the chemical industry and its lobbyists, as well as the American public.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Around that time, Carson learned that *Silent Spring* had been selected as the Book of the Month for October; she said this would "carry it to farms and hamlets all over that country that don't know what a bookstore looks like—much less *The New Yorker*".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Other publicity included a positive editorial in *The New York Times* and excerpts of the serialized version were published in *Audubon Magazine*.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] There was another round of publicity in July and August as chemical companies responded.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The story of the birth defect-causing drug thalidomide had broken just before the book's publication, inviting comparisons between Carson and Frances Oldham Kelsey, the Food and Drug Administration reviewer who had blocked the drug's sale in the United States.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In the weeks before the September 27, 1962, publication, there was strong opposition to *Silent Spring* from the chemical industry.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] DuPont, a major manufacturer of DDT and 2,4-D, and Velsicol Chemical Company, the only manufacturer of chlordane and heptachlor, were among the first to respond.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] DuPont compiled an extensive report on the book's press coverage and estimated impact on public opinion.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Velsicol threatened legal action against Houghton Mifflin, and *The New Yorker* and *Audubon Magazine* unless their planned *Silent Spring* features were canceled.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Chemical industry representatives and lobbyists lodged a range of non-specific complaints, some anonymously.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Chemical companies and associated organizations produced brochures and articles promoting and defending pesticide use.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] However, Carson's and the publishers' lawyers were confident in the vetting process *Silent Spring* had undergone.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The magazine and book publications proceeded as planned, as did the large Book-of-the-Month printing, which included a pamphlet by William O.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] American Cyanamid biochemist Robert White-Stevens and former Cyanamid chemist Thomas Jukes were among the most aggressive critics, especially of Carson's analysis of DDT.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] According to White-Stevens, "If man were to follow the teachings of Miss Carson, we would return to the Dark Ages, and the insects and diseases and vermin would once again inherit the earth".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Others attacked Carson's personal character and scientific credentials, her training being in marine biology rather than biochemistry.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] White-Stevens called her "a fanatic defender of the cult of the balance of nature".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] According to historian Linda Lear the former US Secretary of Agriculture Ezra Taft Benson, asked in a letter to former President Dwight D.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Eisenhower, "Why a spinster with no children was so concerned about genetics?" Benson's conclusion was Carson was "probably a Communist".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Monsanto published 5,000 copies of a parody called "The Desolate Year" (1962) which projected a world of famine and disease caused by banning pesticides.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Many critics repeatedly said Carson was calling for the elimination of all pesticides, but she had made it clear she was not advocating this but was instead encouraging responsible and carefully managed use with an awareness of the chemicals' impact on ecosystems.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] She concludes her section on DDT in *Silent Spring* with advice for spraying as little as possible to limit the development of resistance.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Mark Hamilton Lytle writes, Carson "quite self-consciously decided to write a book calling into question the paradigm of scientific progress that defined postwar American culture".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The academic community—including prominent defenders such as H.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Muller, Loren Eiseley, Clarence Cottam and Frank Egler—mostly backed the book's scientific claims and public opinion backed Carson's text.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The chemical industry campaign was counterproductive because the controversy increased public awareness of the potential dangers of pesticides, an early example of the Streisand Effect.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Pesticide use became a major public issue after a *CBS Reports* television special, *The Silent Spring of Rachel Carson*, which was broadcast on April 3, 1963.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The program included segments of Carson reading from *Silent Spring* and interviews with other experts, mostly critics including White-Stevens.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] According to biographer Linda Lear, "in juxtaposition to the wild-eyed, loud-voiced Dr.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Robert White-Stevens in white lab coat, Carson appeared anything but the hysterical alarmist that her critics contended".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Reactions from the estimated audience of ten to fifteen million were overwhelmingly positive and the program spurred a congressional review of pesticide hazards and the public release of a pesticide report by the President's Science Advisory Committee.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Within a year of publication, attacks on the book and on Carson had lost momentum.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In one of her last public appearances, Carson testified before President John F.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Kennedy's Science Advisory Committee, which issued its report on May 15, 1963, largely backing Carson's scientific claims.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Following the report's release, Carson also testified before a US Senate subcommittee to make policy recommendations.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Though Carson received hundreds of other speaking invitations, she was unable to accept most of them because her health was steadily declining, with only brief periods of remission.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] She spoke as much as she could, and appeared on *The Today Show* and gave speeches at several dinners held in her honor.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In late 1963, she received a flurry of awards and honors: the Audubon Medal from the National Audubon Society, the Cullum Geographical Medal from the American Geographical Society, and induction into the American Academy of Arts and Letters.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The book was translated into many languages including German, French, Dutch, Japanese, Russian and Italian.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson's work had a powerful impact on the environmental movement.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] *Silent Spring* became a rallying point for the new social movement in the 1960s.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] According to environmental engineer and Carson scholar H.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Patricia Hynes, "*Silent Spring* altered the balance of power in the world.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] No one since would be able to sell pollution as the necessary underside of progress so easily or uncritically." Carson's work and the activism it inspired are partly responsible for the deep ecology movement and the strength of the grassroots environmental movement since the 1960s.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] It was also influential to the rise of ecofeminism and to many feminist scientists.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Carson's most direct legacy in the environmental movement was the campaign to ban the use of DDT in the United States, and related efforts to ban or limit its use throughout the world.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The 1967 formation of the Environmental Defense Fund was the first major milestone in the campaign against DDT.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The organization brought lawsuits against the government to "establish a citizen's right to a clean environment", and the arguments against DDT largely mirrored Carson's.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] By 1972, the Environmental Defense Fund and other activist groups had succeeded in securing a phase-out of DDT use in the United States, except in emergency cases.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The creation of the Environmental Protection Agency by the Nixon Administration in 1970 addressed another concern that Carson had written about.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Until then, the USDA was responsible both for regulating pesticides and promoting the concerns of the agriculture industry; Carson saw this as a conflict of interest, since the agency was not responsible for effects on wildlife or other environmental concerns beyond farm policy.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Fifteen years after its creation, one journalist described the EPA as "the extended shadow of *Silent Spring*".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Much of the agency's early work, such as enforcement of the 1972 Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act, was directly related to Carson's work.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Contrary to the position of the pesticide industry, the DDT phase-out action taken by the EPA (led by William Ruckelshaus) implied that there was no way to adequately regulate DDT use.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Ruckelshaus' conclusion was that DDT could not be used safely.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In a 2013 interview, Ruckelshaus briefly recounted his decision to ban DDT except for emergency uses, noting that Carson's book featured DDT and for that reason the issue drew considerable public attention.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Former Vice President of the United States and environmentalist Al Gore wrote an introduction to the 1992 edition of *Silent Spring*.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] He wrote: "*Silent Spring* had a profound impact ...
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] These arguments have been dismissed as "outrageous" by former World Health Organization scientist Socrates Litsios.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] May Berenbaum, University of Illinois entomologist, says, "to blame environmentalists who oppose DDT for more deaths than Hitler is worse than irresponsible".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Investigative journalist Adam Sarvana and others characterize this notion as a "myth" promoted principally by Bate.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In the 1990s and 2000s, campaigns against the book intensified, in part due to efforts by the tobacco industry to cast larger doubt on science-driven policy as a way of contesting bans on smoking.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In 2009, the heavily corporate-funded CEI set up a website falsely blaming Carson for deaths to malaria.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] This triggered a point-by-point rebuttal by biographer William Souder, who reviewed the distortions used by campaigners against *Silent Spring*.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Biographer Hamilton Lytle believes these estimates are unrealistic, even if Carson can be "blamed" for worldwide DDT policies.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] John Quiggin and Tim Lambert wrote, "the most striking feature of the claim against Carson is the ease with which it can be refuted".
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] DDT was never banned for anti-malarial use, and its ban for agricultural use in the United States in 1972 did not apply outside the US nor to anti-malaria spraying.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The international treaty that banned most uses of DDT and other organochlorine pesticides—the 2001 Stockholm Convention on Persistent Organic Pollutants (which became effective in 2004)—included an exemption for the use of DDT for malaria control until affordable substitutes could be found.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Mass outdoor spraying of DDT was abandoned in poor countries subject to malaria, such as Sri Lanka, in the 1970s and 1980s; this was not because of government prohibitions but because the DDT had lost its ability to kill the mosquitoes.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Because of insects' very short breeding cycle and large number of offspring, the most resistant insects survive and pass on their genetic traits to their offspring, which replace the pesticide-slain insects relatively rapidly.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Agricultural spraying of pesticides produces pesticide resistance in seven to ten years.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Some experts have said that restrictions placed on the agricultural use of DDT have increased its effectiveness for malaria control.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] According to pro-DDT advocate Amir Attaran, the result of the (activated in 2004) Stockholm Convention banning DDT's use in agriculture "is arguably better than the status quo ...
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In 1996, a follow-up book, *Beyond Silent Spring*, co-written by H.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] F. van Emden and David Peakall, was published.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In 1967, George Newson composed the tape composition *Silent Spring* using birdsong recorded at London Zoo as source material.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] It was premiered at the Queen Elizabeth Hall in January 1968.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] In 2011, the American composer Steven Stucky wrote the eponymously titled symphonic poem *Silent Spring* to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of the book's publication.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] The piece was given its world premiere in Pittsburgh on February 17, 2012, with the conductor Manfred Honeck leading the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.
[src:silent-spring/silent-spring] Naturalist David Attenborough has stated that *Silent Spring* was probably the book that had changed the scientific world the most, after the *On the Origin of Species* by Charles Darwin.
